Zohir et al. (2001) found a significant positive correlation between group functioning and group members’ performances. The success of a microfinancial organization depends on the group formation that brings joint liability among the group members especially through peer selection, peer monitoring, and peer pressure (Godquin, 2004). Loan recovery is expected to increase through social ties and homogenous groups because they facilitate peer monitoring (Besley and Coats, 1995). Moreover, Zeller (1998) has found that there are positive effects of group lending which results in higher repayment. Earlier studies have emphasized the effectiveness of peer selection and group homogeneity in leading to higher repayment rates (Ghatak, 1999 and Zeller, 1998). An empirical study on 128 credit groups from Grameen Bank, ASA and BRAC in Bangladesh by Sharma and Zeller (1997) suggested that variation of assets owned by the group members, even if it is little different in terms of land owned, has a negative impact upon the group. Sharma and Zeller (1999) confirmed that ASA maintained the following criteria regarding their prospective borrowers’ selection:


land owned by the borrowers is less than one half acre;

monthly income is not over TK1200;

people sell labour for at least 200 days in a year.

Karlan and Validivia (2007) have found that training is useful for microcredit in terms of high repayments rates and client retention. After receiving training, participants are able to show greater business knowledge, including keeping records of their businesses, and are also able to reduce sales fluctuations. Sharma and Zeller (1997) have shown that ASA, BRAC, PROSHIKA provide training activities in different areas such as entrepreneurial skill development, managing micro enterprises, shop keeping, crafts production, general awareness, family planning activities, and so forth. However, Karlan and Validivia (2007) warned that the programmes were losing some clients due to the duration of meetings that took place every week, putting people off from seeking further loans. It is claimed by Langer et al. (1999) that more than 90% of programmes in the US focus on training activities, having transferred from an earlier focus on loans. By contrast, developing countries like Bangladesh, Indonesia, and Bolivia used to focus on training but they are currently focusing more on loans (Schreiner and Woller, 2003). Servon (2001) has revealed that some fund providers prefer to pay for the loans rather than training but some of them still provide training to their borrowers in order to get funds from donors. Schreiner and Morduch (2001) have disclosed four reasons for avoiding training activities in developing countries:


most of the businesses are relatively simple and lenders expect borrowers to know about their businesses;

borrowers will blame lenders’ training programmes in case of project failure – so lenders may face problem of getting regular instalments from borrowers;

it does not necessarily follow that an efficient lender would be an efficient trainer; and finally,

training programmes incur some extra costs for the lenders.
